# WHAT IT IS
#   `pending-dns` is a **programmable authoritative DNS server**
#   designed for organizations that need to manage thousands of
#   tenant-controlled DNS zones (multi-tenant SaaS, mass-hosting
#   reseller platforms, dynamic-DNS providers, CDN edge fleets,
#   serverless-platform DNS layers) without the operational
#   overhead of BIND9 zone files + reload signals.
#
#   Architecture:
#
#     • **API layer**  — Hapi-based REST server on
#       `--api.host:--api.port` (default 127.0.0.1:5080).
#       Every operation is a POST/GET/PUT/DELETE against the
#       zone-records collection — create a zone, update an A
#       record, delete a CNAME, list records, with full JSON
#       request/response.
#
#     • **DNS layer**  — pure-Node.js authoritative DNS server
#       on `--dns.host:--dns.port` (default 127.0.0.1:5053)
#       built on the dns2 library; responds to UDP + TCP DNS
#       queries with zone data fetched from Redis (cached
#       in-process for low-latency hot-zone serving).
#
#     • **Storage layer**  — Redis-backed zone-data store
#       (`--dbs.redis <URL>`).  All zones + records persist
#       in Redis; multiple `pending-dns` processes can share
#       the same Redis instance for horizontal scaling.
#
#     • **ACME layer**  — built-in Let's-Encrypt ACME-DNS-01
#       challenge solver.  Configure an ACME email + domain
#       and pending-dns auto-creates the
#       `_acme-challenge.<domain>` TXT records during the
#       certificate-issuance flow, signs them, removes them
#       on completion — no manual zone-file editing.
#
#     • **Worker pool**  — multi-process worker pool spawned
#       via Node.js `worker_threads`; per-worker resource
#       limits, graceful restart on crash.
#
#   Suitable as the DNS backend for hosting providers, ISPs,
#   email-delivery platforms (Andris Reinman uses it inside
#   the Postal Systems commercial email-routing platform for
#   per-customer DKIM key + SPF record management), and any
#   organization that wants programmatic DNS zone management
#   without the BIND9 operational toolchain.
#
